1. Enable Windows Defender Antivirus and Anti-Malware Protection
* Action: Make sure Windows Defender is enabled to protect against viruses, malware, and other threats.
* How:
Open Settings → Update & Security → Windows Security.
Click on Virus & Threat Protection.
Ensure that Virus & Threat Protection settings are turned on.
Enable Cloud-delivered protection and Automatic sample submission for more effective detection of threats.

2. Enable Windows Firewall
* Action: The Windows Firewall should be enabled to block unauthorized access to your computer.
* How:
Open Control Panel → System and Security → Windows Defender Firewall.
Click on Turn Windows Defender Firewall on or off.
Ensure that the firewall is enabled for both Private and Public networks.

3. Enable Automatic Updates
* Action: Ensure your system receives the latest security patches and updates automatically.
* How:
Open Settings → Update & Security → Windows Update.
Click on Advanced options and ensure Automatic (recommended) is selected.
Enable Receive updates for other Microsoft products to keep all software up to date.

4. Use Strong Passwords and Enable Password Complexity
* Action: Use complex passwords for all user accounts to prevent unauthorized access.
* How:
Open Control Panel → User Accounts → Change account type.
Set strong passwords that include a mix of upper and lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters.
Enforce password complexity by enabling Local Group Policy Editor:
Press Win + R, type gpedit.msc, and hit Enter.
Navigate to Computer Configuration → Windows Settings → Security Settings → Account Policies → Password Policy.
Enable Password must meet complexity requirements.

5. Enable BitLocker Drive Encryption
* Action: Use BitLocker to encrypt your hard drive and protect sensitive data from unauthorized access.
* How:
Open Control Panel → System and Security → BitLocker Drive Encryption.
Turn on BitLocker for your system drive (usually C:).
Follow the steps to set up a recovery key and encryption options.

6. Use Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)
* Action: Enable 2FA for online accounts and services to add an additional layer of protection.
* How:
Enable Microsoft Authenticator or a third-party 2FA app on your Microsoft account.
Use Windows Hello for biometric authentication (facial recognition, fingerprint) to log in securely.

7. Enable Secure Boot
* Action: Secure Boot helps protect against rootkits and bootkits by ensuring that only trusted operating systems and bootloaders can run on your machine.
* How:
Restart the computer and enter the BIOS/UEFI settings by pressing the appropriate key (usually F2, Del, or Esc).
Navigate to the Boot tab and ensure Secure Boot is enabled.
Save and exit the BIOS.

